Q: for .1uf and .1nf bypass capacitors what package (0402 vs 0603) do you suggest

For a modern, high-performance chip like the **nRF54L15**, the choice between 0402 and 0603 is less about "hand-solderability" and more about **Parasitic Inductance** and **High-Frequency Performance**.

### 1. The Short Answer: Go with 0402
For a low-power, high-frequency BLE design using the nRF54L15, I strongly suggest using **0402 (1005 Metric)** packages for both the $0.1\mu\text{F}$ and $100\text{pF}$ ($0.1\text{nF}$) capacitors.

### 2. Why 0402 is better for this project

#### A. Lower Parasitic Inductance ($ESL$)
Bypass capacitors are there to "soak up" high-frequency noise. At the clock speeds and radio frequencies (2.4GHz) of the nRF54 series, the physical size of the component matters. 
* Smaller components (0402) have shorter internal paths and smaller solder pads.
* This results in lower **Equivalent Series Inductance ($ESL$)**. 
* High $ESL$ limits how fast the capacitor can respond to high-speed switching noise. 0402 outperforms 0603 in this regard.



#### B. Higher Self-Resonant Frequency ($SRF$)
The $100\text{pF}$ ($0.1\text{nF}$) capacitor is likely intended to filter very high-frequency noise or assist near the radio/DC-DC blocks. 
* A 0402 capacitor will have a higher **Self-Resonant Frequency** than a 0603. 
* Above the $SRF$, a capacitor actually starts behaving like an inductor and stops being useful for bypassing. You want your $SRF$ to be as high as possible.

#### C. PCB Real Estate
The nRF54L15 is a very small SoC. Using 0603 capacitors will force you to place them further away from the power pins.
* **The Golden Rule of Bypassing:** The effectiveness of a bypass capacitor is inversely proportional to its distance from the IC pin.
* 0402s allow you to pack the decoupling network extremely tight to the nRF54, which is critical for passing EMI/EMC testing.

---

### 3. Comparison Table

| Feature | 0402 (1005 Metric) | 0603 (1608 Metric) | Winner |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **High-Frequency Performance** | Excellent ($Low\ ESL$) | Average | **0402** |
| **Placement Proximity** | Can be very close to IC | Requires more space | **0402** |
| **Hand Soldering** | Possible with tweezers/magnification | Very easy | **0603** |
| **DC Bias Effect** | Slightly more sensitive | Better (less capacitance loss) | **0603** |

### 4. A Note on "DC Bias"
One area where 0603 usually wins is the **DC Bias Effect** (where the effective capacitance drops as you apply voltage). However, at $1.8\text{V}$ or $3.3\text{V}$, the difference between a 0402 and 0603 for a $0.1\mu\text{F}$ capacitor is negligible. Just ensure you specify **X7R** or **X5R** dielectric rather than Y5V.

### Final Recommendation
* Use **0402** for all bypass caps ($0.1\mu\text{F}$ and $100\text{pF}$).
* If you are worried about hand-soldering, use a **"Long-Pad" 0402 footprint** in your PCB software; it makes it much easier to get the soldering iron tip onto the pad without losing the component.

**Would you like me to check the specific dielectric requirements (like NP0/C0G vs X7R) for your 100pF caps to ensure they are stable for the nRF54 radio?**


